Text.Value: My prowess in battle does the talking for me - I have no need of your 'stories'.
I heard you may be affiliated with the arsonists who destroyed our Steel Watch protectors.
But alas. Any articles not about Gortash's death might as well be bog roll at the moment.

EditorData.NodeContext: a bit more to himself, he's ignoring the player thinking about the articles he's comissioning

Text.Value: I'm not afraid of you. Lord Gortash is a passionate champion of the journalistic arts - attack me, and you face the Steel Watch.
Perhaps a bit of coin could make the article go away?
Now, GUARDS! I believe our distinguished guest was just leaving. Would you care to escort them out?
Hah! Caught you! Bet you thought you were so clever sneaking back in... GUARDS!
You know I've done far, far worse than that, right?
Not many enter our fine city and immediately start meddling in murder investigations. Curious, don't you think?
Attack the guards.
I'd rather you spread the word about the one I serve. I have some suggestions, if you'd like.
I'd rather not be in your paper at all. Anonymity is helpful in my... business.
Seems odd you've written the article before asking me any questions.
Leave.
Lord Gortash is going to destroy me. I swear, you'll rue the day you crossed Ettvard Needle.
Print that about me and I'll push your corpse through the Gazette printworks.
You'd like me to add bribery to your list of extra-legal pursuits? How bold.
A shame it was never published - I always wanted to be in the Baldur's Mouth.
A shame it was never published - I always wanted to be in a broadsheet.
It'll be your word against mine - and I'm really good with words.
I know you meddled with my printing press. I know you published that fluff piece about yourself.
Shall I add 'lying cretin' to your long list of misdeeds? You speak nonsense.

EditorData.logicalname: POS ARTICLE PUB G DEAD 2nd GREET

Text.Value: Stop the article, or I'll cook you from the inside out.
Nice try - but it's not going to work. Lord Gortash and me are very close and he mentioned no such thing to me.
This letter proving you're Gortash's puppet would make a better headline.
...Oh, really? I'm all ears, my quill dipped, dunked, and ready to tell the world whatever you wish to confess.
Are you sure you have enough ink to cover all my adventures?
Would these blackmail letters from Gortash delay publication?
Oh, you gave us plenty to work with.
I have more than stories - ballads, prose, even a haiku or two, if you can spare the ink.
I'm working with Lord Gortash. He wouldn't want bad rumours spread about me.
I've never heard of so much violence against innocent circus freaks before.
We have plenty of ink. Enough to cover all your misadventures in this good city.
Well, you should've considered that before disgracing yourself in public.
How is one meant to cover a dead duke with an equally dead printing press...? Simply can't supply the demand...

EditorData.NodeContext: muttering to self, clearly very stressed ignoring player

Text.Value: Well, well, if it isn't the city's next celebrity! You star in our next edition's top story.
If anything bad is printed about me, your obituary will follow soon after.
Leave.
How long is this article? Because I've got a lot of stories - and I only blow up in some of them.
And then we can only hope the Fist do their duty and escort you to the gallows! Your days scumming up this good city's streets will be over.
If anything bad is printed about me, I'll leak this letter to you from Lord Gortash.
Imagine a chronicle of your deeds, written in bile on the skin of fools.
Pray tell - how exactly will you disseminate that information? What's the name of your highly popular broadsheet? No? Exactly.
How long is this article? I'd love to publish some of own my magical theories.
You again. Old news - I've got a dead duke to commemorate. Be on your way.
Estra deals with the personal interviews and fluff pieces. I deal with the truth. And the truth is - you're a damned menace.
I'd rather your paper focus on more pressing things - like this city, and how it squanders nature's gifts.
Say - I know that face. We had an absolute blinder of a piece ready to print about you. Would've been your ruin, I reckon.
No need to introduce yourself. I make sure I become intimately familiar with my subjects before writing about them.
Sorry, who are you?
We will stick to our existing story, and you're fortunate that's all.
That's the spirit - better people spit your name than not say it at all.
Yeah - I heard all about your article, and I want you to shut it down.
If you think bothering me will delay your article being published, you're quite deluded.
Since your arrival, reports of Absolutist activity in this city have increased tenfold. Hardly seems a coincidence.
Let the guards take you outside.
You think I'd dedicate precious column space to a miscreant like you when a lord's just died? Do get a grip.
Ettvard Needle. Editor of the Baldur's Mouth Gazette. Speaking truth to power since 1450 DR.
The guards will see you out.
How about a piece on siege tactics? Or self-defence? I have plenty of suggestions.
Oh, I know plenty about you already, knave.
However, column space is a rare commodity when a lord dies. So you can consider the tales of your misdeeds indefinitely postponed.
I might have to check in with my patron about that first - see how they feel about being in the spotlight.
I would never reveal my sources, and certainly not to the likes of you. Besides, you're too late.
I'd be terrified if I hadn't changed the article already.
We can still publish, but Gortash'll have my hide if I don't fix the printworks - You! Get out of here, I'm busy!

EditorData.NodeContext: muttering to self, then notices the player after hyphen

Text.Value: I'd rather not be in your paper at all.
Why were you writing something negative about me?
Who told you this nonsense?
If what you've just said is true, pissing me off is a bad idea. Stop the article.
*With great difficulty, you throw aside the desire to toot your own terror-trumpet for this smut-peddler.*
Suit yourself - be sure to have a gander at tomorrow's edition - you star.
And I also know it doesn't matter. Sure, some will read it - but you're no dead duke. You're old news. To be forgotten.
Trafficking refugees into our city is hardly a good look. Especially when so many are Absolutists and murderers.
First I will break your printer. Then I will break YOU. STOP THE ARTICLE.
The headlines are loaded into the printworks already. Tomorrow you will feel the power of free speech. Vox populi, vox dei.
The truth will be out with tomorrow's broadsheet. People will spit in your face. Your very presence will be bad for business. You'll be a pariah. An outcast. As you should be.
*Your tongue slithers over your glory like the snake it is, tasting each misdeed once again.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: DARK URGE GRINS - DARK URGE RAGE GRAPHIC PLAYS

Text.Value: Now, take your leave. I have so many articles to arrange for the next edition - dead men might tell no tales, but they certainly sell them.
Bite your tongue. Grant them mercy from your horrible tale.
You'll never know, though.
Gods, the untold depravity... it is unprintable. I'll be out of syndication if I publish your gore-smut confessional.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: When the dark urge leaves the frenzy of their imagination, Ettvard is shocked.

Text.Value: I have no need of such attention. I suggest you focus on something useful - like the obvious corruption in this city.
I did, until I swapped out the articles. You'll smear me no more.

Synopsis:
Ettvard Needle is the editor of the Baldur's Mouth Gazette. He is proudly pro-Gortash, obnoxious towards the PC, and insinuates (wel, directly states at the moment)  that the gazette is about to print a hit piece about the players.

Players can intimidate Ettvard for some info, or use blackmail on him if they have found it to keep the hit piece from being published.
